        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(qa): wire Crabline fake provider runtimes",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nThis is now the third PR in the split stack from the original broad #95920. The Slack channel foundation lives in #97154, and the WhatsApp channel foundation lives in #97155.\n\nThis PR only wires QA Lab's Crabline transport to the fake-provider runtimes and updates QA Lab to the published @openclaw/crabline release that advertises Slack and WhatsApp fake providers.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nQA Lab needs per-channel fake-provider setup that stays outside the channel plugins. Slack can use the standard SLACK_API_URL path from #97154, while WhatsApp can register a socket factory through the runtime-setter seam from #97155.\n\nThe QA Lab side now resolves explicit fake-provider runtime handlers by channel, errors for unsupported Crabline fake-provider channels, stages the WhatsApp auth dir, installs the WhatsApp socket hook only when the Crabline WhatsApp env is present, and passes runtime env patches into gateway runs.\n\n## User Impact\n\nNormal OpenClaw runtime behavior is unchanged. QA Lab runs using the crabline channel driver can target Telegram, Slack, and WhatsApp fake-provider servers from Crabline 0.1.3.\n\nStack:\n- Slack foundation: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/97154\n- WhatsApp foundation: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/97155\n- QA Lab Crabline wiring: this PR\n\n## Evidence\n\n- pnpm install --frozen-lockfile\n- node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/qa-lab/src/crabline-transport.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/fake-provider-runtime-hooks.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/suite.test.ts\n- pnpm tsgo:extensions\n- git diff --check\n\nKnown remaining gate: dependency-guard still requires exact-head maintainer/security approval for the @openclaw/crabline package bump.\n",
        "branch": "codex/crabline-provider-env-wiring",
